Motivation and Background

Give an overview of the project, motivation, background and goals.

Stories can be told through various mediums, and can be retold in different ways through adaptation of the source material into other media. This offers a new experience to a familiar title, especially for fans of the original material, and allows creators to make more money from their intellectual property. I believe that such adaptations are becoming more popular to create recently for these reasons, and would like to investigate more on their history and whether they really are profitable at all.

Summary of Research Questions & Results

Repeat your research questions in a numbered list. After each research question, clearly state the answer/conclusion you determined. Do not give details or justifications yet just the answer
  1. How has the number and popularity of adaptations created changed over time?
  • Their numbers have generally increased but have been decreasing recently.
  • Novel to film adaptations have become more popular recently, but there is no significant trend.
  1. How well do film adaptations sell?
  • Very well.

# First, we want to merge the film budgets and sales data into a single dataframe.  
# To do this, we will need to merge on both the movie title and release year,
# since some movies have the same title but different release years.
film_data = pd.merge(film_sales_data, film_budgets_data, how='outer', on=['Movie', 'Year'])

# formatting numerical columns
film_data[['Production Budget','Worldwide Box Office','Worldwide Gross']]\
    = film_data[['Production Budget','Worldwide Box Office','Worldwide Gross']]\
        .replace(regex='[\$,]', value='').astype(float)

# Since the 'WorldwideBox Office' and 'WorldwideGross' columns represent the same data,
# I will take the sales to be the larger value between the two columns in each row,
# as it is likely the more recent value.
film_data['Sales'] = film_data[['Worldwide Box Office','Worldwide Gross']].fillna(0).max(axis=1)

# taking useful columns
film_data = film_data.iloc[:,[1,5,6,9]].copy()

# removing all empty values and duplicates
mask = (film_data['Sales'] == 0) | (film_data['Release Date'] == 'Unknown')
film_data = film_data.drop(film_data[mask].index).drop_duplicates().reset_index(drop=True)

# format date
film_data['Release Date'] = pd.to_datetime(film_data['Release Date'])

In[20]:
# renaming columns
vg_data = vg_data.rename(columns={
    'Critic Score': 'CriticScore',
    'Total Sales': 'SalesInMillions',
    'Release Date': 'ReleaseDate'
})

# For all rows, there is always data in either the Total Shipped column or the Total Sales column,
# but never both. 
# For the sake of simplicity, I will therefore take them to represent the same data
# and merge the columns.
vg_data['SalesInMillions'] = vg_data['SalesInMillions'].fillna(vg_data['Total Shipped'])

# Similarly, I will merge the VGChartz Score and CriticScore columns.
# In this case, I will take the CriticScore column to be more reliable
# since it averages ratings from various sources.
vg_data['CriticScore'] = vg_data['CriticScore'].fillna(vg_data['VGChartz Score'])

# formatting columns
vg_data['SalesInMillions'] = pd.to_numeric(vg_data['SalesInMillions'].str[:-1])
vg_data['ReleaseDate'] = pd.to_datetime(
    vg_data['ReleaseDate'].replace(regex='(\d)(st|nd|rd|th)', value='\\1'),
    format="%d %b %y")

# dropping unneeded data
vg_data = vg_data[vg_data['SalesInMillions']!=0.0].iloc[:,[0,1,4,6,7]]\
    .drop_duplicates().reset_index(drop=True)
vg_data = vg_data[vg_data['Console'] != 'Series']

# remove duplicates if there is an entry with console 'All'
consoles = vg_data.groupby('Title')['Console'].apply(''.join)
has_all = consoles[consoles.str.contains('All') & (consoles.str.len()>3)].index
has_all = vg_data[vg_data['Title'].isin(has_all)].drop_duplicates(subset='Title')
vg_data = vg_data[~vg_data['Title'].isin(has_all['Title'])]\
    .merge(has_all, how='outer')

# merge sales in rows with the same title but different console
vg_data['SalesInMillions'] = vg_data.groupby('Title')['SalesInMillions']\
    .transform('sum')
vg_data = vg_data.drop_duplicates(subset=['Title'])\
    .sort_values(by=['SalesInMillions', 'Title'], ascending=False)\
        .reset_index(drop=True).iloc[:,[0,2,3,4]]

film_novel_data = film_novel_data[film_novel_data.columns[[0,1,3,7]]]

# remove the reference brackets
film_novel_data = film_novel_data.replace(regex='\[.*?\]', value='')

# fill in NaN release years
years = film_novel_data['Title'].str.extractall('\((\d{4})\)')[0]
years.index = years.index.droplevel(level=1)
film_novel_data.loc[years.index.get_level_values(0), 'Release Date'] =\
    film_novel_data.loc[years.index.get_level_values(0), 'Release Date'].fillna(years)

# Some release dates specify the month or even the day
# For consistency, I will only keep the year
film_novel_data = film_novel_data.dropna(subset='Release Date')
film_novel_data['Release Date'] = film_novel_data['Release Date'].str[-4:].astype(int)

# drop useless characters
film_novel_data['Title'] = film_novel_data['Title'].replace(' \(\d{4}\)', '', regex=True)
film_novel_data['ISBN'] = film_novel_data['ISBN'].str.split('/').str[0].replace('-', '', regex=True)

film_novel_data = film_novel_data.rename(columns={'Release Date': 'Year'})

# renaming columns
novel_film_data.columns = ['Original', 'Adaptation']

# extracting release year   
novel_film_data = novel_film_data.merge(
    novel_film_data['Original'].str.extractall('\((\d{4})s?\)').groupby(level=0)\
        .agg(list).rename(columns={0:'OriginalReleaseYear'}),
    how='left', left_index=True, right_index=True)

# same thing, regex does not include 's?' as those cases are not in this column
novel_film_data = novel_film_data.merge(
    novel_film_data['Adaptation'].str.extractall('\((\d{4})\)').groupby(level=0)\
        .agg(list).rename(columns={0:'AdaptReleaseYear'}),
    how='left', left_index=True, right_index=True)

# remove bracketed parts
#novel_film_data = novel_film_data.replace('\(.*\)', '', regex=True)

# extracting titles
novel_film_data = novel_film_data.merge(
    novel_film_data['Original'].str.split('\*+ *\**|(?<=[a-z])(?=[A-Z])').rename('OriginalTitle'),
    how='left', left_index=True, right_index=True)
novel_film_data = novel_film_data.merge(
    novel_film_data['Adaptation'].str.split('\*+ *\**|(?<=\))(?=[A-Z])').rename('AdaptTitle'),
    how='left', left_index=True, right_index=True)

# remove entries with '(series)'
mask = novel_film_data['OriginalTitle'].str.len() >\
    novel_film_data['OriginalReleaseYear'].str.len(), 'OriginalTitle'
novel_film_data.loc[mask] = novel_film_data.loc[mask].str[1:]

def clean_title(s):
    novel_film_data[s] = novel_film_data[s].map(lambda l: list(map(lambda s: s.split(' (')[0], l)))
clean_title('OriginalTitle')
clean_title('AdaptTitle')

novel_film_data = novel_film_data.dropna(subset=['OriginalReleaseYear', 'AdaptReleaseYear'])
novel_film_data = novel_film_data.drop(columns=['Original', 'Adaptation'])

Q1. How has the number and popularity of adaptations created changed over time?

I will first plot a histogram for all of the categories combined.

In[31]:
# extract release years
def dates_data(df: pd.DataFrame):
    if 'AdaptReleaseDate' in df.columns:
        return df['AdaptReleaseDate'].dt.year
    elif 'Year' in df.columns:
        return df['Year'].dropna().astype(int)
    else:
        return df['AdaptReleaseYear'].explode().astype(int)

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
dates = pd.concat(list(map(dates_data, df_list)))
sns.histplot(dates, bins=range(1890,2026,5), edgecolor='w', kde=True);

From the graph, it seems that 2005-2010 was the period of time with the most adaptations, and 2005 in particular was the peak.
The number of adaptations increased up to almost 600 from 2005-2010, and then sharply decreased afterwards, which seems interesting since one would expect that over time, there would be more original material to produce adaptations out of, and therefore more adaptations produced.
I will now plot a histogram for each of the eight categories using small multiples.

To better visualise the revenue of these films, I will create a violin plot using revenue, which is (sales - budget).

In[39]:
revenue = film_adapt_data['Sales'] - film_adapt_data['Production Budget']

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))

plt.plot((0,0), (0.4,-0.4), color='red')
plt.xlabel("Revenue")
plt.title("Distribution of Film Adaptation Revenue");

From the graph, we can see that the first quartile is approximately 0, and the median and mode are just slightly above that. That is, about 25% of film adaptations actually lose money, and another 25% seem to make a small amount of revenue.
However, this amount appearing small could be due to the movies with higher revenue simply having more budget, therefore having more sales and revenue, a correlation established earlier.
I will try to create a fairer distribution by instead finding the ratio of budget to sales, and plotting that. In this case, net losses will result in a ratio of between 0 and 1, while net profits will have a ratio greater than 1.

In[40]:
sales_budget_ratio = film_adapt_data['Sales'] / film_adapt_data['Production Budget']

plt.xlabel("Sales to Budget Ratio")
plt.title("Distribution of Film Adaptation Sales to Budget Ratio");

This graph has a very similar shape to the previous one, which is certainly unexpected. The possible presence of some bias towards more expensive movies in the previous graph has not led to any observable change in this one. (not related to question, covered in appendix at bottom of report)

As a comparison, I will plot the same distribution, but also with all films.

In[41]:
sales_budget_ratio2 = film_data['Sales'] / film_data['Production Budget']

plt.suptitle("Distribution of Film Sales to Budget Ratio")
fig.tight_layout(pad=2)

We see that film adaptations generally have a greater sales to budget ratio than all films. There is also a smaller percentage of film adaptations that make a loss as compared to all films.
We conclude that, relative to other films, film adaptations sell better.
